      "top_gaps": [
        {
          "id": "PRD-034",
          "severity": "critical",
          "label": "Preserve saved libraries across data-model upgrades",
          "why": "The plan tracks schema versioning, but it never commits to automatic carry-forward of every saved show and every My Data field across upgrades. If this remains implicit, a migration could be technically \u201csafe\u201d while still failing the benchmark\u2019s continuity promise."
        },
        {
          "id": "PRD-005",
          "severity": "critical",
          "label": "Configure build through env without code edits",
          "why": "The plan includes env loading and examples, but it never states the benchmark\u2019s stronger repo contract that setup must be entirely env-driven. That leaves a compliance gap around reproducible runs for fresh agents."
        },
        {
          "id": "PRD-085",
          "severity": "important",
          "label": "Keep one consistent AI persona across surfaces",
          "why": "The plan covers general AI quality and references voice indirectly, but it does not explicitly lock Scoop, Ask, Explore Similar, and Alchemy to a single shared persona. Without that, the product can ship with individually \u201cgood\u201d AI surfaces that still feel like different products."
        },
        {
          "id": "PRD-088",
          "severity": "important",
          "label": "Structure Scoop as personal taste mini-review",
          "why": "The plan mentions a \u201cWorth it?\u201d style and voice adherence, but it omits most of the concrete Scoop section contract. That risks an implementation that generates generic blurbs instead of the specific mini-review format users are meant to recognize."
        },
        {
          "id": "PRD-076",
          "severity": "important",
          "label": "Return bullet-only, 1-3 word, non-generic concepts",
          "why": "The plan protects word count and specificity, but not the bullet-only output form. If concept generation drifts into prose or sentence fragments, Explore Similar and Alchemy lose both UI consistency and steerability."
        }
      ],
      "narrative": {
        "overall_posture": "This is a strong plan with a relatively small number of meaningful holes. It is not missing the product\u2019s core mechanics: the collection model, namespace/user isolation, persistence boundaries, Search, Detail, Ask, Explore Similar, Alchemy, Person Detail, Settings, export, and the main testing strategy are all planned concretely. The overall posture is \u201cimplementation-ready with targeted spec fidelity gaps,\u201d not \u201cstructurally unsound.\u201d",
        "strength_clusters": "The plan is strongest in benchmark infrastructure, identity/persistence architecture, and the major end-user workflows. The benchmark rider requirements are handled well: Next.js, Supabase, namespace isolation, user scoping, reset tooling, env files, migrations, and source-of-truth rules are all explicitly planned. The core collection and discovery flows are also well-covered: Home filtering/grouping, save/remove defaults, overlay merge behavior, Search, Detail page sections, Ask mentions, Explore Similar counts, Alchemy chaining, and export all have concrete implementation tasks and verification coverage.",
        "weakness_clusters": "The weaker coverage clusters around behaviorally specific product contracts rather than missing whole features. Most partials sit in three buckets: AI persona fidelity, Detail-page UX micro-contracts, and a handful of benchmark-compliance nuances. The plan tends to say \u201cfollow the voice spec\u201d or \u201cuse the detail-page spec\u201d instead of restating the exact user-visible contracts, which leaves gaps around consistent persona across all AI surfaces, Scoop structure/copy states, Ask summarization constraints, concept output formatting, and the explicit env-only benchmark setup rule.",
        "risk_assessment": "If the team executed this plan unchanged, the most likely failure mode is not a broken app. It is a product that mostly works but drifts at the edges where the benchmark is most opinionated: AI surfaces may feel tonally inconsistent, Scoop may read like a generic summary instead of the intended taste-review format, concept chips may be fed by looser outputs than the spec allows, and migration/env-handling compliance could be questioned during benchmark review. A stakeholder or QA reviewer would probably notice that first in the AI/discovery experience and benchmark setup checklist, not in the CRUD flows.",
        "remediation_guidance": "The remaining planning work is mostly specification tightening, not architectural redesign. The plan needs a small number of sharper acceptance criteria around migration continuity, benchmark setup guarantees, AI persona invariants, Scoop\u2019s exact structure and state behavior, and concept formatting contracts. Those gaps should be fixed by adding explicit behavioral requirements and test assertions, not by changing the high-level system design."
      },
