      "top_gaps": [],
      "narrative": {
        "overall_posture": "This is a structurally strong plan with meaningful behavioral gaps. It covers the benchmark substrate, core schema, main screens, and most of the primary journeys well enough to execute, and the critical coverage score is high at 92.0%. The overall score lands at 80.1% because the missing or partial items cluster around product-contract details rather than the basic build path.",
        "strength_clusters": "The plan is strongest in infrastructure and persistence scaffolding, collection CRUD, search, and the broad shape of the major discovery flows. Namespace isolation, `user_id` partitioning, migrations, scripts, Supabase boundaries, save/update/remove flows, status grouping, export, and the multi-phase AI surface buildout are all concretely planned. The plan also does a good job of translating the PRD into executable phases, especially for home/search/detail/alchemy mechanics.",
        "weakness_clusters": "The gaps are not random. They cluster in three places: AI behavioral contracts, nuanced UX states, and subtle persistence rules. On the AI side, the plan captures endpoints and prompts but under-specifies guardrails such as off-domain handling, parse-failure retry, exact concept quality constraints, shared persona consistency, and the acceptance bar for \u201csurprise without betrayal.\u201d On the UX side, the plan includes the right detail-page sections but does not preserve the narrative order or smaller required states like `No tags`, `No results found`, and last-selected filter persistence. On the data side, it covers the big schema decisions but leaves sync dedupe, settings conflict resolution, and full technical storage-shape fidelity only partially specified.",
        "risk_assessment": "If this plan were executed as-is, the most likely failure mode is a build that works mechanically but feels less intentional than the PRD. A stakeholder would probably first notice that Ask, Scoop, Explore Similar, and Alchemy behave like adjacent AI features rather than one coherent product voice, and QA would likely catch missing edge-state behavior around filter persistence, empty states, or AI parsing fallback. A second-order risk is data inconsistency over time: the app would likely save and read records correctly, but sync and migration edge cases would remain underspecified.",
        "remediation_guidance": "The remediation work is mostly planning refinement, not a wholesale rewrite. The next pass should add explicit acceptance criteria for AI outputs, a dedicated section for sync/conflict/migration behavior, and concrete UX requirements for the detail-page order and filter/empty-state handling. In other words, the plan needs tighter behavioral specifications and validation criteria around the product\u2019s \u201cheart,\u201d plus a small number of persistence and state-management clarifications, rather than major architectural changes."
      },
